docs.abstract: A temporary cease-fire has calmed fears of a trade war, but the Trump administration now faces criticism it is backing down from striking a tough deal.
docs.snippet: A temporary cease-fire has calmed fears of a trade war, but the Trump administration now faces criticism it is backing down from striking a tough deal.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration has suspended its plan to impose sweeping tariffs on China as it presses forward with trade talks, a gesture that will temporarily ease tensions between the two nations but rapidly increase pressure on President Trump to secure the type of tough deal that he has long said is necessary to protect American workers.

headline.main: U.S. Suspends Tariffs on China, Stoking Fears of a Loss of Leverage
headline.print_headline: U.S. Suspends Tariffs Against China, Stoking Fears of Loss of Leverage

byline.original: By Ana Swanson and Alan Rappeport

docs.abstract: A ramped-up immigration system after the 9/11 terror attacks put strict limits on foreign travelers even before President Trump’s “extreme vetting” order.
docs.snippet: A ramped-up immigration system after the 9/11 terror attacks put strict limits on foreign travelers even before President Trump’s “extreme vetting” order.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump took office promising to enact an “extreme vetting” immigration system with a travel ban that he said would keep terrorists from exploiting the visa system and getting into the United States.

headline.main: U.S. Vetting System Already Robust Before Travel Ban, Report Finds
headline.print_headline: Want ‘Extreme Vetting’? U.S. Has Had It for Years

docs.abstract: Facing intense criticism, Customs and Border Protection denied accusations that its officers had separated families and turned away migrants seeking asylum at official ports of entry.
docs.snippet: Facing intense criticism, Customs and Border Protection denied accusations that its officers had separated families and turned away migrants seeking asylum at official ports of entry.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Facing a barrage of criticism over their agency’s role in carrying out the Trump administration’s “zero tolerance” immigration policy at the border, officials at Customs and Border Protection went on the offensive on Monday to deny claims that officers at official ports of entry had separated families and turned away migrants seeking asylum in the United States.

headline.main: Migrant Families Who Enter at Legal Ports Are Rarely Separated, Customs Officials Say
headline.print_headline: Customs Officials Rebuff Family Separation Claims

docs.abstract: Senior Trump administration officials said in Senate testimony that they were not aware of the “zero tolerance” policy that resulted in family separations until it was announced.
docs.snippet: Senior Trump administration officials said in Senate testimony that they were not aware of the “zero tolerance” policy that resulted in family separations until it was announced.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Not until the day it was announced did senior officials from three key agencies learn of the Trump administration’s “zero tolerance” policy to deter migrants from illegally entering the United States by threatening jail sentences and separating children from their parents.

headline.main: Migrant Detention Centers Are ‘Like a Summer Camp,’ Official Says at Hearing
headline.print_headline: Official Likens Shelters to Summer Camp

docs.abstract: The Department of Health and Human Services learned of the missing children only after calling people who took responsibility for the youths when they were released from government custody.
docs.snippet: The Department of Health and Human Services learned of the missing children only after calling people who took responsibility for the youths when they were released from government custody.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A top official with the Department of Health and Human Services told members of Congress on Thursday that the agency had lost track of nearly 1,500 migrant children it placed with sponsors in the United States, raising concerns they could end up in the hands of human traffickers or be used as laborers by people posing as relatives.

headline.main: Federal Agencies Lost Track of Nearly 1,500 Migrant Children Placed With Sponsors
headline.print_headline: Agency Says  It Lost Track Of Nearly 1,500  Child Migrants

docs.abstract: The Trump administration called the money for building new and replacement barriers a first step in the president’s promise for a border wall with Mexico.
docs.snippet: The Trump administration called the money for building new and replacement barriers a first step in the president’s promise for a border wall with Mexico.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration said on Friday that it could immediately fund 100 miles of new and replacement border fencing, a first step in the president’s plans for building a wall on part of the United States’ nearly 2,000-mile border with Mexico.

headline.main: U.S. Says It Can Pay for 100 Miles of Wall on 2,000-Mile Border
headline.print_headline: U.S. Says It Can Finance 100 Miles of Border Wall

docs.abstract: Lawmakers are pushing for billions in new funding for biomedical research, but sparring over health insurance and almost everything else related to the Affordable Care Act.
docs.snippet: Lawmakers are pushing for billions in new funding for biomedical research, but sparring over health insurance and almost everything else related to the Affordable Care Act.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — They cannot agree on subsidies for low-income people under the Affordable Care Act or even how to extend funding for the broadly popular Children’s Health Insurance Program — two issues requiring urgent attention as Congress returns to work.

headline.main: Medical Research? Congress Cheers. Medical Care? Congress Brawls.
headline.print_headline: Medical Research? Congress Cheers. Medical Care? Congress Brawls.

docs.abstract: The president said he would promote more competition among pharmaceutical companies, but didn’t call for Medicare to directly negotiate lower prices or consumers to be able to import low-cost drugs.
docs.snippet: The president said he would promote more competition among pharmaceutical companies, but didn’t call for Medicare to directly negotiate lower prices or consumers to be able to import low-cost drugs.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump vowed on Friday to “bring soaring drug prices back down to earth” by promoting competition among pharmaceutical companies, and he suggested that the government could require drugmakers to disclose prices in their ubiquitous television advertising.

headline.main: Trump Promises Lower Drug Prices, but Drops Populist Solutions
headline.print_headline: Drug Plan Drops Populist Designs, Not the Rhetoric

docs.abstract: A budget deal billed as a measure to stabilize government funding is chock-full of provisions that have consequences for the health care system.
docs.snippet: A budget deal billed as a measure to stabilize government funding is chock-full of provisions that have consequences for the health care system.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The budget deal in Congress is billed as a measure to grant stability to a government funding process that has lurched from crisis to crisis — but it is also stuffed with provisions that will broadly affect the nation’s health care system, like repealing an advisory board to curb Medicare spending and funding community health centers.

headline.main: From Clinics to Child Insurance, Budget Deal Affects Health Care
headline.print_headline: In Budget Deal, Provisions to Reshape Health Care

docs.abstract: The administration said it would restore the program to avoid causing chaos for consumers should health plans become insolvent or withdraw from the market.
docs.snippet: The administration said it would restore the program to avoid causing chaos for consumers should health plans become insolvent or withdraw from the market.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration, in an abrupt reversal, said Tuesday that it would restart a program that pays billions of dollars to insurers to stabilize health insurance markets under the Affordable Care Act.

headline.main: Trump Administration, in Reversal, Will Resume Risk Payments to Health Insurers
headline.print_headline: White House Will Resume  Risk Payments to Insurers
